{
  "texts": [
    "As the advent of quantum computers looms ever closer, the super computing power it provides would cause threats on the security of universally used cryptographic schemes in various application fields by the Shor's algorithm (Shor 1999), this is based on a polynomial-time quantum algorithm proposed by Shor which can be used to factor large integers and solve discrete logarithm problem.",
    "Thus, the schemes based on the number-theoretic hard problems and discrete logarithm problem tend to be vulnerable which cover almost all public-key encryption wildly used on the Internet including RSA (Rivest et al. 1978), DSA (National Institute of Standards and Technology 2009), and elliptic-curve cryptography (Breuil and Diamond 2001).",
    "For 30 years, Shor's algorithm has been an example of the promise of quantum computers.",
    "Until Oded Regev, recently proposes a scheme (Regev 2023) that drastically reduces the number of gates or logical steps needed to factor extremely large numbers, which is the first substantial improvement of Shor's algorithm in 30 years.",
    "In principle, it could allow a smaller quantum computer to figure out the encryption key, or a larger machine to decode the encryption key more quickly."
  ]
}